Introduction & Background:¶

Our data science tutorial is built around the data regarding the top streamers on Twitch. Our tutorial provides various analyses regarding streaming minutes, viewers, and followers of these top streamers.

Gaming has always been a huge industry and each year it only grows bigger. Every year millions of dollars are invested into various games and gaming platforms and the revenue is massive. Twitch is a live streaming video service, mainly popular for their video game live streams. Twitch has been used to broadcast ESports comptitions, as well as music broadcasts, and other creative content. It is a platform used by millions of people around the world and we found an analysis on it would prove useful for others wanting to learn more about this industry.

Motivation:¶

During 2020 as Covid-19 swept through every nation, the world was mostly confined to their homes and in turn the popularity of Twitch only grew bigger. In February 2020, the streaming service had almost 15 million daily active users and around 3 million bradcasters. We wanted to analyze the top streamers of Twitch in 2020 to observe how various variables affect streams. Not only will this analhysis be beneficial for Twitch streamers thmselves but it will also help provide an analysis for individuals curious as to how and why streaming is so popular on Twitch. Using our data set we can determine things such as if the number of followers gained affects how much time a creator streams. Or if a streamers content rating can be beneficial for them to gain followers. All these analyses will hopefully prove to be beneficial for new and old stramers in figuring out how to improve their platform and gain followers. Twitch has continuously been a popular streaming platform so it would be extremly useful to provide an analysis using the data of the streams on this widly used service.

Preliminary Analysis¶

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.heatmap(data.corr(), annot=True, cmap='Reds')
plt.show()

Before begininng our analysis we wanted to get an overall sense of the variables and how they relate with eachother. We determined that the best way to visualize this would be through a heat map. In our heat map above we can observe that variables with a darker color represent a higher correlation. Obviously variables will have a magnitude of 1 with itself, but along with that we can observe how other variables interact with eachother. The darker the square indicated to us that it would be useful to observe the relationship between the two variables in some sort of way later on in our analysis. For instance followers and total watch time was found to have a high magnitude along with average viewers and watch time. Certain boxes of the heat map weren't that useful such as the magnitude between average viewers and peak viewers which you would expect to have a high magnitude. However all in all the heat map was a very useful tool in getting us started with deciding what visualizations we want to make and what relationships we wanted to graph.

Top 25 Streamers vs...¶

Top 25 Streamers vs Stream Time:¶

In [ ]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))
ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])
mins = list(data['Stream time(minutes)'])
channel = list(data['Channel'])

plt.title('Top 25 Streamers vs Stream Time', fontsize=18)
ax.set_ylabel("Stream Time (minutes)")
ax.set_xlabel("Streamer Name")
ax.bar(channel[:25], mins[:25])
for tick in ax.get_xticklabels():
    tick.set_rotation(85)
plt.show()

Our graph above was created to visualize (if there is any) a relationship between the top 25 Twitch streamers and the amount of time which they streamed in minutes. The top streamers were determined by their total watch time. The goal of this plot was to determine if we can correlate stream time with the popularity of streamers. Overall the stream time seems to be somewhat varied and on the lower side. We can observe that the top 4 streamers do indeed havee significantly higher stream minutes but the remaining 21 don't stream nearly as much as the top 4 streamers do. This leads us to belieeve there can't be too big of a dependency of popularity based on how much you stream. For instance streamer "Tfue" streamed around 40,000 minutes less than the next top streamer yet he's still in the Top 5 streamers of Twitch based on watch time.

Looking at the Top 10 Streamers¶

Our first graph will be a pie chart looking at the top 10 Twitch streamers determined by their followers. We'll use a pie graph in order to visualize the percentage of followers each streamer has out of the top 10.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

followers = list(data["Followers"])[:10]

plt.pie(followers, labels=channels, autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.show()

Our second graph will be a pie chart looking at the top 10 Twitch streamers determined by their average viewers. We'll use a pie graph in order to visualize the percentage of viewers each streamer has out of the top 10.

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.title('Top 10 Channels based on Average Viewers', fontsize=18)
avg = list(data["Average viewers"])[:10]
channels = list(data["Channel"])[:10]
plt.pie(avg, explode=None, labels=channels, autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.show()

Between the two pie charts we can observe that just because a streamer has a high following count it doeesn't imply that the streamer will have a higher average number of viewers. For instance in graph 1 streamer "Asmongold" only made up 4.4% of the pie chart based on his followers but when we jump to graph 2 we see that "Asmongold" takes up the largest proportion of the graph at 19.1% based on his average views. The oopsoite scenario can be seen with streamer "ESL_CSGO" who went from 11.1% in the followers graph to only 3.5% in the number of views graph. These cases along with others shows us that having high followers doesn't guarantee high views and vice versa.

Linear Regression of All Streamers¶

For our last visualization our goal was to create a linear regression to predict the watch time of a streamer based on the number of followers they had.

In [ ]:
def get_regression_model(df, x, y):
   model = LinearRegression()
   X = [[x] for x in df[x].values]
   y = [[y] for y in df[y].values]
   rfit = model.fit(X, y)
   rscore = model.score(X, y)
   return model, rfit, rscore
   
unique_f = [[x] for x in data['Followers'].unique()]
model, rfit, rscore = get_regression_model(data, 'Followers', 'Watch time(Minutes)')
ax = data.plot('Followers', 'Watch time(Minutes)', kind='scatter', c='r', figsize=(18, 13))
ax.set_title('Followers vs Watch Time(Minutes) of All Streamers', fontsize=18)
ax.plot(unique_f, [y for [y] in model.predict(unique_f)], c='blue')
plt.show()

After running our linear regression we found that watch_time = 423.79(followers) + 1.768e08) with an R^2 value of 0.385. So in conclusion our model predicts a positive relationship between watch time and followers, more specifically if a streamer gains 1 million followers his watch time should increase by about 424 minutes. Our p-values are lower than 0.05 indiicating that our variables are significant. However our r-squared values was pretty low, being only 0.385. One highly likely reason as to why this value is so low is because when looking at our scatter plot we see that a significant portion of our data is concentrated in one area. There aren't many data points throughout the graph thus it's hard to build a strong correlation since most of our data is focused in one area. This prevents us from having a high r-squared value because the correlation doesn't follow throughout the graph. We could potentially increase our r-squared value and accuracy by adding more variables to the regression.

Conclusion¶

In this tutorial, we wanted to analyze the dataset of the top 1000 Twitch streamers around the world. Analyzing the information we got from the dataset along with visual representations of it allowed us to dive deeper into the correlation between different variables and if it helps a streamer become a top streamer. From this, we discovered that for the top 10 streamers just because a streamer has a high number of followers doesn't equate to them having a high watch time. Often time streamers with lower follower counts would have greater total watch time than streamers with much more followers. This allows streamers to know that just because their follower count isn't as high as others they shouldn't be discouraged and that they can still become a top streamer based on total watch time. We also saw that in the top 25 streamers a high follower count or high number of views didn't seem to equate to being a more popular streamer. This again lets individuals know they shouldn't be discouraged if their number of followers isn't high, their watch time can still be high and they can still be a top streamer. We then looked at the top 100 and the bottom 100 streamers and saw that in the top 100 streamers followers and watch time were concentrated in one area whereas for the bottom 100 the watch time was all over the place. In the end we performed a linear regression between followers and watch time to see if we could find a relationship. We saw that there was a positive trend between followers and a streamers watch time however the correlation was somewhat low with r-squared value being a 0.385. The linear regression did lead us to conclude that there is somewhat of a small correlation and that as your number of followers increase your watch time should increase as well.

The data that we analyzed helped us have a better understanding about what really makes a twitch streamer be in the top percentile. Based on the analysis of each subcategory, some streamers had a lot more average viewers, some streamers had a lot more average watch time ,and some had a lot more followers than other. All of this information helped us determine that to be a top streamer, there are a variety of different factors that come into play and no one should be discouraged if they are lacking in one category.
